Input/Output, Variables & Keywords 🐍⌨️📦

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

🧠 Introduction

In Python, programs interact with users using:

✔ Input  
✔ Output  
✔ Variables  
✔ Keywords  

These are the foundation of programming.

---

🔹 What is Input?

```text id="input_def"
Input is data provided by the user to the program.
````

---

🔹 What is Output?

```text id="output_def"
Output is the result displayed by the program.
```

---

💻 Output Example

```python id="output_example"
print("Welcome to Python")
```

---

▶️ Output

```text id="output_result"
Welcome to Python
```

---

⌨️ Taking User Input

```python id="input_example2"
name = input("Enter your name: ")

print("Hello", name)
```

---

▶️ Example Output

```text id="input_output_example"
Enter your name: Saakshi
Hello Saakshi
```

---

🔢 Input Always Returns String

By default, `input()` returns data as a string.

---

💻 Example

```python id="string_input_example"
age = input("Enter age: ")

print(type(age))
```

---

▶️ Output

```text id="string_output"
<class 'str'>
```

---

🔄 Type Conversion

We use type casting to convert data types.

---

💻 Integer Input Example

```python id="integer_input_example"
age = int(input("Enter age: "))

print(age)
print(type(age))
```

---

🔹 Common Type Casting Functions

| Function  | Purpose            |
| --------- | ------------------ |
| `int()`   | Convert to integer |
| `float()` | Convert to float   |
| `str()`   | Convert to string  |
| `bool()`  | Convert to boolean |

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

📦 Variables in Python

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

🔹 What is a Variable?

```text id="variable_def2"
A variable is a container used to store data.
```

---

💻 Variable Example

```python id="variable_example2"
name = "Python"
version = 3.13

print(name)
print(version)
```

---

📌 Variable Naming Rules

✔ Can contain letters, numbers, `_`
✔ Cannot start with numbers
✔ Cannot use spaces
✔ Case-sensitive

---

✅ Valid Variable Names

```python id="valid_variables"
student_name = "Rahul"
age2 = 20
_total = 500
```

---

❌ Invalid Variable Names

```python id="invalid_variables"
2name = "Python"
user-name = "Alex"
class = 10
```

---

🧠 Multiple Variable Assignment

```python id="multiple_variables"
x, y, z = 10, 20, 30

print(x)
print(y)
print(z)
```

---

🔄 Swapping Variables

```python id="swap_variables"
a = 5
b = 10

a, b = b, a

print(a)
print(b)
```

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

🔑 Keywords in Python

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

🔹 What are Keywords?

```text id="keyword_def"
Keywords are reserved words with special meanings in Python.
```

---

⚠️ Important Point

Keywords cannot be used as variable names.

---

💻 Example

```python id="keyword_error"
# Invalid

class = 10
```

---

📋 Common Python Keywords

| Keyword    | Purpose               |
| ---------- | --------------------- |
| `if`       | Condition             |
| `else`     | Alternative condition |
| `for`      | Loop                  |
| `while`    | Repetition            |
| `break`    | Exit loop             |
| `continue` | Skip iteration        |
| `def`      | Function creation     |
| `return`   | Return value          |
| `class`    | Create class          |
| `import`   | Import modules        |

---

💻 Print Python Keywords

```python id="keyword_program"
import keyword

print(keyword.kwlist)
```

---

🎯 Real-Life Analogy

| Concept  | Real-Life Example           |
| -------- | --------------------------- |
| Variable | Storage box                 |
| Input    | Asking user for information |
| Output   | Showing result on screen    |
| Keyword  | Reserved command            |

---

🚀 Mini Practice Program

```python id="mini_program"
name = input("Enter your name: ")
age = int(input("Enter your age: "))

print("Name:", name)
print("Age:", age)
```

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

🔧 Best Practices

✔ Use meaningful variable names
✔ Avoid single-letter variables
✔ Follow naming conventions
✔ Do not use keywords as variables

---

⚠️ Common Mistakes

❌ Forgetting type casting
❌ Invalid variable names
❌ Using keywords as variables
❌ Wrong indentation

---

🧠 Interview Answer (Simple)

> Variables store data in Python, input is used to take user data, output displays results, and keywords are reserved words with predefined meanings.

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

📚 Key Takeaways

✔ `input()` takes user input
✔ `print()` displays output
✔ Variables store values
✔ Keywords are reserved words
✔ Type casting changes data types


